Would have to move ~1% in either direction in the final quarter to switch buckets. Possible, but pretty unlikely. Last time it jumped ~1% was in the early pandemic with sublease rates jumping through the roof. They're still elevated, but coming down. Biggest problem I can envision would be a bunch of leases expiring in Q4, but there hasn't been a clear pattern of that in the data, so probably not? Q3 national report has Toronto office vacancy at 10.1%, right in the middle of the 9-11 bucket. While it continues to trend upward, verbiage in the Colliers report suggests that back to office campaigns are ongoing, so I'm not weighting >11 much higher than <9. Not sure if their commentary leans bullish generally or not though.

Update Q4: all districts show a worsening higher vacancy rate. Downtown: 91M ->94M 1.1% ->7.1%Q3->7.3%Q4 = +6.2% (supply possibly going up to 95M has happened). Given the drive for quality and eagerness for hybrid, would possibly expect a stabilisation of things but due to increased space avail the vacancy rate could stay equal. Weighed impact on 250M = 2.6. If we factor an expectation to go from 7.1 vacancy to 6.1%, weighed impact 2.32%. I stay with this fcst Midtown: 24M: 1.6% -> 5.4%Q3->6.0% = +4.4%. Expectd to stay equal as those are business parks, consumer areas. The 0.6% increase was not expected. Weighed impact to be 0.6% GTA North / East: 76M: 4.9% -> 8.1%->8.3%Q4 = 3.2%. Available went from 76M to 72M and still Vacancy increased to 8.3%. Reduce 0.7%, weighed impact 2.4%. GTA West: 62M: 8.0% -> 12.3%->12.7% = +4.7%. Available went down to 59,5M and still vacancy went up to 12.7%. Possibly some reduction weighed impact 2.4% Total: 7.5% lower bound Total: 8.7% + acceleration hybrid (+1%) and few recovery at airport: 9.5%-10%. This scenario has lower chance but few is needed to actually make the last bucket.

Increase in vacancy rate appears to be leveling off. But how many companies are just waiting until they can get out of their lease? Net absorption for Q3 2021 is still negative, though some areas have positive absorption.

I believe the vacancy rate has already started to fall, it will fall further but not return to pre pandemic. The tail is Likely longer than the end of 2022 so I think it will be in the 6.5-7.5% range, more likely slightly less than 7%

Since 2019, 7 quarters of increasing vacancies and so far no reversal. If we assume pandemic continues through Q4 2021 & Q1 2022, that gives us maybe 3 quarters during which this could plausibly reverse with any magnitude. Possible there is a rush back to the office next summer/fall, but equally possible that there is continued atrophy over the next 2 quarters that has to be made up for.
I think a lot of companies will terminate their leases whenever they become eligible over the next 14 months.
